"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"**On everyday little questions with big answers**\\n\\n*(Originally published on [Showing My Working](https://showingmyworking.substack.com/p/whats-your-name).)*\\n\\n## Iceberg Questions\\n\\nThere are common questions everyone gets asked that seem to require a simple and short answer but can go much deeper. The expected short answer may be the 10% tip that appears above the surface, with 90% of it hidden below, deep and heavy.\\n\\n![](https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2e37a7f-6e24-411a-a9c4-f7de75dbd7ab_829x577.png)\\n\\nIâ€™ve known for a long time that â€œwhere are you \\\\[really\\\\] from?â€ is one such question for me, and many others and othereds. Another deep and heavy question I encountered recently is â€œhow many siblings do you have?â€ when asked of someone who has grieved the loss of a brother. I canâ€™t fathom the complexity of emotions that would touch.\\n\\nIâ€™ve now discovered that for me â€œWhatâ€™s your name?â€ is another.\\n\\n## The Answers to â€œWhatâ€™s Your Name?â€\\n\\nâ€œAmirâ€.\\n\\nWhatâ€™s iceberg-y about that? For most people most of the time, itâ€™s not. I didnâ€™t think it was for me either. But then I went and did the silly thing of paying attention to my feelings and found the deep and heavy ğŸ¤¦ğŸ½â€â™‚ï¸\\n\\nIt started with doing a seemingly cringey â€˜meet your inner childâ€™/reparenting exercise with my therapist. I just couldnâ€™t connect to the kid in the memory I had picked. I tried choosing a different memory. Tried to zhuzh myself up and blow away the scepticism. But it wasnâ€™t happening. I gave up for a few days.\\n\\n![I always was a bit too serious, even as a child.](https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fefeefe13-4b9d-46e1-bc54-8d521c07e274_1076x1600.jpeg)\\n\\nWhen I tried again later, alone, I was a bit looser. The conversation between adult and child me still felt stilted and awkward so I kept resetting. Then something clicked. I changed my mental language to Persian and called the child what he was called at the time.\\n\\n**â€œSalaam, Amirhossein!â€**\\n\\nAhhh! He looked up! His face was more open! I used his actual frigginâ€™ name and he engaged!\\n\\nI insist on *Amir H. Hajizamani* wherever I can. I use *amirhhz* as my handle. A nod, but not full recognition. A dissociation hidden in plain sight. Iâ€™ve often felt self-conscious or pompous for insisting that my initials be included in seemingly unimportant displays of my name (bank cards are my pet peeve). But Iâ€™ve still felt compelled to include it. Unlike many other things in my life, the fear of judgement from others never stopped me insisting on this one letter. And I never thought much of this until the experience above.\\n\\nSome people might be thinking: â€œWell, itâ€™s not very unusual for people to be attached to their middle name, or include it as standard. Whatâ€™s the big deal?â€\\n\\nSure. Let me take you to another scene, one thatâ€™s a staple part of my conversational programming.\\n\\n> *Person:* â€œHi, whatâ€™s your name?â€\\n>\\n> *Me (brain):* \\\\[Oh, make sure you donâ€™t say â€œIâ€™m â€¦â€ because that sound melts too easily into â€œAmirâ€ and people end up mishearing.\\\\]\\n>\\n> *Me:* â€œHiya, my name is Amirâ€\\n>\\n> *Me (brain):* \\\\[Queue up spelling in case of a â€œSorry, what?â€ to avoid the 3 awkward back-and-forths situation\\\\]\\n>\\n> *Person:* â€œA-mir? Or a-MEER?â€\\n>\\n> *Me (brain):* \\\\[Ugh, both are wrong, especially if youâ€™ve a British accent and donâ€™t roll your Râ€™s\\\\]\\n>\\n> *Me:* â€œEither is fine.â€\\n>\\n> *Person:* â€œNice â€¦ so where are you from?â€\\n>\\n> *Me:* \\\\[RUNS OUT SCREAMING\\\\]\\n\\nThe last bit is in jest / for another episode. But what I want to illustrate is that even in this best-case scenario, I rarely hear my name said correctly. Even the shortened version.\\n\\nA more annoying version thatâ€™s been happening recently:\\n\\nI know this white person who seems to invest a lot of their sense of identity in promoting social justice and being angry about the world. They have been calling me â€œAA-merâ€, the South Asian-style pronunciation of the name. Iâ€™ve never introduced myself as such, they never asked how Iâ€™d like my name pronounced, and no-one else calls me that in the contexts we share together. Iâ€™m certain this is well-intentioned and perhaps they feel theyâ€™re doing a great job of saying my name correctly, according to whatever experience they have.\\n\\nI know it doesnâ€™t seem like a big deal, and that I should correct them the next time it happens (I will, potentially risking having to deal with their white fragility about it). But every time Iâ€™ve heard them say my name so *innovatively* wrong itâ€™s been like a flick behind the ear. Not a big deal, but it happens enough times, you get pissed. I know itâ€™s my boundary to set (and again, I will at the next opportunity) but the point here is that even the most well-intentioned people contribute to the degradation and dissociation of my sense of self that I need to negotiate and modulate one way or another.\\n\\n## History of a Name\\n\\nHow does one get to being dissociated from their own name and their past?\\n\\nWhen I was first enrolled in a British school at the age of 12, it was under the name â€œAmir Zamaniâ€. This was a bid by my parents to simplify things for the British people I would be encountering - ever the Good Immigrants they were. Occasionally, I would delight at my initials being â€œAZâ€. I felt an irreverent joy at helping people with the pronunciation even further by saying â€œrhymes with Armaniâ€. I changed schools twice in two years and repeated this shtick each time. It became ingrained.\\n\\nA year or two later, I was picking subjects for my GCSEâ€™s. Somehow, I clocked onto the fact that my name would appear on my certificates and that it would not match my passport and other official documents (matching what my family actually called me was an afterthought). I asked my parents to â€œfixâ€ my name at the school to â€œAmir Hossein Hajizamaniâ€. I now had a middle name. Iâ€™d never had a middle name before. Just â€œAmirhosseinâ€. Yes, my family would \\\\*shock horror\\\\* say the WHOLE thing each time theyâ€™d call me.\\n\\nAs far as I know, thereâ€™s no particular significance to â€œAmirâ€ or â€œHosseinâ€ - fairly common names in Iranian culture. The minor significance according to my parents is that within their social circle at the time, giving children these â€œdoubleâ€ names was Ã  la mode, and within my cohort of cousins I was the first to be given a double name. Many others in our extended family followed suit, so I guess my parents felt like trendsetters or something.\\n\\nBut even a mediocre name can only take so much beating. In assimilating into a new culture, Iâ€™d lost part of my given and family name, then Iâ€™d regained them in a different structure, and to this day, most people donâ€™t even say my amputated name properly. Letâ€™s not even get started on â€˜Hajizamaniâ€™ (FWIW: itâ€™s incredibly phonetic, no tricks, just say the syllables, two letters at a time).\\n\\n## So â€¦ What IS Your Name, man?!\\n\\nLook, this already feels like such a self-indulgent and narcissistic post - scrolling up and down and seeing so many mentions of my name makes me feel pretty uncomfortable.\\n\\nSo let me be clear: Iâ€™m not asking anyone to learn and practice the pronunciation of â€œAmirâ€ to make me feel better, or to call me â€œAmir Hosseinâ€ all of a sudden - I mean whoâ€™s got the time when youâ€™ve so got many sourdough breads to make or whatever.\\n\\nIâ€™m just sharing this. Perhaps making up for years of ceding ground when it comes to my name by taking a little bit of Internet space about it now.\\n\\nThereâ€™ll be people of a variety of backgrounds who might relate to what Iâ€™ve described here to some degree. Whether you do or you donâ€™t, be mindful but avoid guilt about saying someoneâ€™s â€œweirdâ€ name badly. Donâ€™t make it awkward for them, just do your best and ask for help if the context seems appropriate, or listen to how they say it and just do that. Just beware that that person is already that tiny bit more drained than you from just doing introductions.\\n\\nAnd Iâ€™m going to go and hear what little Amirhossein has to say, now that Iâ€™ve successfully introduced myself to him.\\n\\n![](https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff76e2187-f5de-4f33-8157-3e446fa16787_3010x3502.jpeg)\\n\\n\",\"timestamp\":1634683856,\"title\":\"â€œWhatâ€™s Your Name?â€\"},\"digest\":\"0pS7GjH-ZZL309ZTCx0VpLICG-Vhr3a6Mui2XP5t3RM\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0x9d482035e912430c11119ed93a8A2f9b6e7ed88b\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"ZWuL9BxD2km3OU8jfgryrw43VcDvg6YrGG1wYSDK2JM\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"YJgMLHbDP6xdBzL3HQvAma8FKQWIRP4TA1OaMu1zjQw\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"Ki0Z6coMsJ40i3HW1iqMXbVDjVUlEryKXFXOdJwulstGIC7dgSWsOnQKnbJtnnRl9T9_QZ9qykj0kkaEb2PG9g\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x8da1be734bbe68d31f1fff54779942da8b065714b8e06877097e1ac101e213b535214d7a0b3cb52962a9a86ee23df2a6526721d10bcfd7e29de7923c1f88a4571b\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I authorize publishing on mirror.xyz from this device using:\\n{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"ZWuL9BxD2km3OU8jfgryrw43VcDvg6YrGG1wYSDK2JM\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"YJgMLHbDP6xdBzL3HQvAma8FKQWIRP4TA1OaMu1zjQw\\\"}\",\"algorithm\":{\"name\":\"ECDSA\",\"hash\